               <p>799. <persName id="def1-799-18440205" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-799-18440205" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-799-18440205" type="surname" value="NEWMAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-799-18440205" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">HENRY NEWMAN</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18440205-799-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18440205-799-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18440205-799-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="forgery"></interp> for feloniously forging an accep<lb></lb>tance to a bill of exchange for 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.;, with intent to defraud <persName id="t18440205-name-1483" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1483" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1483" type="surname" value="MARKWICK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1483" type="given" value="MARK"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18440205-799-offence-1 t18440205-name-1483"></join>Mark Markwick</persName>.—2nd <hi rend="smallCaps">COUNT</hi>, for uttering the same.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. CLARKSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">DOANE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1484" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1484" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1484" type="surname" value="MARKWICK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1484" type="given" value="MARK"></interp>MARK MARKWICK</persName>
                  </hi>. I reside in Hooper-street, Red Lion-square. I have some property in the neighbourhood of Romford, in Essex—I was living at Brixton in 1842—I had occasion to build some houses at Romford and Brentwood—Mr. Edwards introduced me to the prisoner, and he entered into a contract with me for taking some land, and building houses upon it—I adv<lb></lb>anced him money weekly to pay his men, and on other occasions—in March and April, 1843, he borrowed money of me—he borrowed 13<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; for a parti<lb></lb>cular purpose—he said there was an innkeeper to whom be owed some money, and I think he had a bill due for 13<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.;, and begged I would let him have 13<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; to pay it—I gave him a check for 13<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.;—he said Mr. Pain had disappointed him in a loan or payment of money to him, and on the following Wednesday he would bring me the 13<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.;—he never returned that money to me—he con<lb></lb>tinued working for me for about three months—his advances from time to time became much greater than the work he had done, and I found him in great difficulties, so that he could not keep on the spot to look after his men—when I applied to him about the 13<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.;, he said he would get me a bill of 30<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; of Mr. Pain's, at two months' date—I had never seen Mr. Pain—I had heard of him by name, and believed him to be a respectable man, a surveyor—no particular time was named for the bill—it went on from week to week, I be<lb></lb>came alarmed, and pressed him to bring me Mr. Pain's bill for 30<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.;—on the 17th of May he brought me this bill at two months for 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.;, stating that Mr. Pain refused to give a bill for more than 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.;, and for a less period than three months—this is the bill—(<hi rend="italic">bill read</hi>)—he told me previously where Mr. Pain lived—when the bill became due, it was presented through my bankers—I never got the money.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1485" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1485" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1485" type="surname" value="PAIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1485" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY PAIN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a surveyor. Last May I was living in Loughborough-road,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184402050223"></xptr>
               <p>North Brixton—the acceptance to this bill it not in my handwriting—I have no recollection of authorising the prisoner to accept this bill, and sign my name to it—I know the prisoner—he has done several jobs for me, and others I have recommended him to.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You have no recollection of having authorised him to sign your name: do you mean, you might have given him authority, and forgot it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I mean, of course, that I might have given him authority—from our conver<lb></lb>sation he might have assumed it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You mean, he might have understood you gave him autho<lb></lb>rity? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He might have done so—we have had several conversations toge<lb></lb>ther—he might have thought so.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DOANE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You have had several conversations, do you mean about bills of exchange? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not bills of exchange particularly—<hi rend="italic">bond fide</hi> matters—I have had several conversations with him about bills of exchange—I have drawn upon him, and he on me—I do not recollect that I ever had any con<lb></lb>versation with him about a bill for 30<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; at two months, or about a bill for 30<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; at all—I cannot say I had not—we may have had conversation about a 30<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; bill about May last—I was examined about this matter before the Justice on two occasions—I do not think my memory has at all improved since then with respect to having or not authorised the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You were examined on oath? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yet—I have a recollec<lb></lb>tion of what I stated on that occasion.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> That being so, do you now mean to say you may have authorised him to use your name by way of acceptance? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I was called very suddenly to go there, and could not bring all the circumstances directly to my mind—I did not know what I was called for hardly—I do not think I ever gave him authority to use my name in putting an acceptance to this bill—I have no recollection of it—I do not recollect that I evgr did—I never taw the bill till after it was due—I never gave him a direct authority to put my name there without my seeing it—he may have misunderstood me, and thought he had that authority—he might have taken it for granted, but not a direct authority I never could.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do I understand you think you may have used such language as may have justified him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> That is my meaning—he might certainly think he was justified in using my name—in his own idea he might think so.</p>
               <p>
